entity, individual freedom and the relationship between government and the market. He argues that in order to properly understand the cultural status of alcohol we need to consider what attitudes to drinking tell us about the principles that underpin our modern, liberal society.The politics of alcohol presents a wide-ranging, accessible and critically illuminating guide to the social, political and cultural history of alcohol in England. Covering areas including law, public policy, medical thought, media representations and political philosophy, it will provide essential reading for anyone interested in either the history of alcohol consumption, alcohol policy or the complex social questions posed by drinking today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDrinking of alcoholic beveragesxHistoryzEngland. 0aDrinking of alcoholic beveragesxSocial aspectszEngland. 0aLiquor lawszEngland. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 16th Century.2bisacsh  a24-hour licensing.  aalcohol.  abinge drinking.  adrinking.  aindividual freedom.  anational identity.  apolitical philosophy.  apublic policy.  asocial risks.  asupermarkets.1 aNicholls, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779332440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793324/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles